 First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":26,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":51,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":64,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":73,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Chetelton was born about 1264, in Baddington, Cheshire, England as the son of Robert De Chettelton. He married Ellen De Baddington about 1282, in Baddington, Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1349, at the age of 86."},"et":{"about 1264–1349":"umbes 1264–1349","1260–Male":"1260–Surnud","1264–1349":"1264–1349","–Male":"Surnud","1260–Female":"1260–Surnud","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","1310–1363":"1310–1363","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","about 1282":"umbes 1282","1363":"1363","1264":"1264","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1235":"1235","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","1276":"1276","about 1264":"umbes 1264","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Badington, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Upper Boddington, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Baddington, Cheshire, England":"Baddington, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1264–1349":"noin 1264–1349","1260–Male":"1260–Kuollut","1264–1349":"1264–1349","–Male":"Kuollut","1260–Female":"1260–Kuollut","1276–Female":"1276–Kuollut","1310–1363":"1310–1363","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","about 1282":"noin 1282","1363":"1363","1264":"1264","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1235":"1235","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","1276":"1276","about 1264":"noin 1264","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Badington, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Upper Boddington, Northamptonshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Baddington, Cheshire, England":"Baddington, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1264–1349":"environ 1264–1349","1260–Male":"1260–Décédé","1264–1349":"1264–1349","–Male":"Décédé","1260–Female":"1260–Décédée","1276–Female":"1276–Décédée","1310–1363":"1310–1363","1235–Male":"1235–Décédé","about 1282":"environ 1282","1363":"1363","1264":"1264","1295":"1295","1260":"1260","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1235":"1235","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","1276":"1276","about 1264":"environ 1264","1328":"1328",